1.2 Br√®ve introduction au but du jeu

Supposons que nous avons deux jeu de donn√©es X et Y.

Dans X, nous avons p variables : \(\textbf{X} = \left(\begin{array}{c}X_1\\X_2\\\vdots\\ X_p\end{array}\right)\) et q variables \(\textbf{Y} = \left(\begin{array}{c}Y_1\\Y_2\\\vdots\\ Y_q\end{array}\right)\) dans le jeu de donn√©es Y

Comme dans une ACP, nous cherchones les combinaisons lin√©aires existant au sein des jeux de donn√©es pour avoir des combinaisons que nous appelerons U et V o√π U sont les combinaisons lin√©aires construites sur le jeu de donn√©es X et V celles fabriqu√©es sur le jeu de donn√©es Y.

En cons√©quence, \(U_{1}\) est une combinaison lin√©aire des p variables constituant X et \(V_{1}\) est la combinaison lin√©aire des q variables composant Y.

\(\begin{array}{ccc} U_1 & = & a_{11}X_1 + a_{12}X_2 + \dots + a_{1p}X_p \\ U_2 & = & a_{21}X_1 + a_{22}X_2 + \dots + a_{2p}X_p \\ & & \vdots \\ U_p & = & a_{p1}X_1 +a_{p2}X_2 + \dots +a_{pp}X_p\\ & & \\ V_1 & = & b_{11}Y_1 + b_{12}Y_2 + \dots + b_{1q}Y_q \\ V_2 & = & b_{21}Y_1 + b_{22}Y_2 + \dots +b_{2q}Y_q \\ & & \vdots \\ V_p & = & b_{p1}Y_1 +b_{p2}Y_2 + \dots +b_{pq}Y_q\end{array}\)

Nous appelerons le couple, \((U_i, V_i)\) la i√®me paire canonique.

Le but du jeu est alors de trouver les combinaisons lin√©aires qui maximisent les corr√©lations entre les membres de chaque variable canonique. Pour cela, il faut √©tudier de tr√®s pr√®s le coefficient de corr√©lation entre Ui et Vi:

\[\text{cov}(U_i, V_j) = \sum_{k=1}^{p} \sum_{l=1}^{q}a_{ik}b_{jl}\text{cov}(X_k, Y_l)\]

Rappelons que :

  • La variance de Ui est \[\text{var}(U_i) = \sum_{k=1}^{p}\sum_{l=1}^{p}a_{ik}a_{il}cov(X_k, X_l)\]

  • La variance de Vi est \[\text{var}(V_j) = \sum_{k=1}^{p} \sum_{l=1}^{q} b_{jk}b_{jl}\text{cov}(Y_k, Y_l)\]

D‚Äôun point de g√©om√©trique, on cherche √† expliquer les combinaisons lin√©aires qui minimisent l‚Äôangle entre U1 et V1.

La corr√©lation cannonique pour le i√®me couple est la corr√©lation entre \[\rho^*_i = \frac{\text{cov}(U_i, V_i)}{\sqrt{\text{var}(U_i) \text{var}(V_i)}} \]

C‚Äôest cette quantit√© que l‚Äôon cherche √† maximiser. Ainsi les coefficients \(a_{11}, a_{12}, \dots, a_{1p}\) et \(b_{11}, b_{12}, \dots, b_{1q}\) sont choisis afin de maximiser la corr√©lation canonique \(\rho^*_1\) du premier couple canonique. Autrement dit, cela revient √† dire que la variance du premier couple canonique est √©gal √† 1.

\(\text{var}(U_1) = \text{var}(V_1) = 1\)

En bref,

On veut trouver les coefficients \(a_{i1}, a_{i2}, \dots, a_{ip}\) et \(b_{i1}, b_{i2}, \dots, b_{iq}\) qui maximise la corr√©lation canonique \(\rho^*_i\) en prenant la contrainte :

\(\text{var}(U_i) = \text{var}(V_i) = 1\),

\(\text{cov}(U_1, U_i) = \text{cov}(V_1, V_i) = 0\),

\(\text{cov}(U_2, U_i) = \text{cov}(V_2, V_i) = 0\),

\(\vdots\)

\(\text{cov}(U_{i-1}, U_i) = \text{cov}(V_{i-1}, V_i) = 0\),

\(\text{cov}(U_1, V_i) = \text{cov}(U_i, V_1) = 0\),

\(\text{cov}(U_2, V_i) = \text{cov}(U_i, V_2) = 0\),

\(\vdots\)

\(\text{cov}(U_{i-1}, V_i) = \text{cov}(U_i, V_{i-1}) = 0\)

3 Muscler les r√©sultats

3.1 Petit dictionnaire des mes lectures (√† impl√©menter pour la suite)

Lire cet excellent papier (tr√®s synth√©tique) : https://ncss-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/themes/ncss/pdf/Procedures/NCSS/Canonical_Correlation.pdf

  • Variate Number = This is the sequence number of the canonical correlation. Remember that the first correlation will be the largest, the second will be the next to largest, and so on.

  • Canonical Correlation = The value of the canonical correlation coefficient. This coefficient has the same properties as any other correlation: it ranges between minus one and one, a value near zero indicates low correlation, and an absolute value near one indicates near perfect correlation. R-Squared

  • The square of the canonical correlation coefficient = This gives the R-squared value of fitting the Y canonical variate to the corresponding X canonical variate.

  • F-Value = The value of the F approximation for testing the significance of the Wilks‚Äô lambda corresponding to this row and those below it. In this example, the first F-Value tests the significance of the first, second, and third canonical correlations while the second F-value tests the significance of only the second and third.

  • Num DF = The numerator degrees of freedom of the above F-ratio.

  • Den DF = The denominator degrees of freedom of the above F-ratio.

  • Prob Level This is the probability value for the above F statistic. A value near zero indicates a significant canonical correlation. A cutoff value of 0.05 or 0.01 is often used to determine significance.

  • Wilks‚Äô Lambda for the canonical correlation is the multivariate generalization of R-Squared. The Wilks‚Äô lambda statistic is interpreted just the opposite of R-Squared: a value near zero indicates high correlation while a value near one indicates low correlation.

3.1.1 Wilks‚Äô Lambda [bonus]

V√©rifier avant tout si il y a une relation - petite soit-elle - entre les deux jeux de donn√©es. Les deux jeux de variables sont peut-√™tre d√©corr√©l√©s entre eux et ne pr√©sente aucune liaison (ind√©pendance statistique)

Pour tester l‚Äôind√©pendance entre les performances financi√®res et les r√©sultats acad√©miques, il faut repartir d‚Äôune r√©gression lin√©aire multiple o√π nous devons essayer de pr√©dire les r√©sultats financiers [variables √† expliquer] en fonction des variables explicatives - les r√©sultats aux tests.

De facto, nous avons p r√©gressions multiples o√π chaque r√©gression multiple cherche √† pr√©dire une variable du premier groupe (le dataset X) en fonction des q variables contenus dans le dataset Y.

\(\begin{array}{ccc}X_1 & = & \beta_{10} + \beta_{11}Y_1 +\beta_{12}Y_2 + \dots +\beta_{1q}Y_q + \epsilon_1 \\ X_2 & = & \beta_{20}+ \beta_{21}Y_1 + \beta_{22}Y_2 + \dots +\beta_{2q}Y_q + \epsilon_2 \\ & & \vdots \\ X_p & = & \beta_{p0} + \beta_{p1}Y_1 + \beta_{p2}Y_2 + \dots + \beta_{pq}Y_q + \epsilon_p \end{array}\)

Dans notre cas pr√©cis, nous avons 3 variables provenant du jeu de donn√©es des performances financi√®res que nous voulons expliquer par les 4 variables composant le jeu de donn√©es Y. Cons√©quemment, nous voulons tester l‚Äôhypoth√®se nulle que ces coefficients de r√©gression (except√© pour les intersections) sont tous √©gaux √† z√©ro. Autrement dit, le premier jeu de variables est ind√©pendant du second jeu de donn√©es.

\(H_0: \beta_{ij} = 0;\) ( i = 1,2, , p; j = 1,2, , q)

Pour faire cela, int√©ressons-nous au Wilks lambda.

ev <- (1 - cc1$cor^2)

n <- dim(psych)[1]
p <- length(psych)
q <- length(acad)
k <- min(p, q)
m <- n - 3/2 - (p + q)/2

w <- rev(cumprod(rev(ev)))

d1 <- d2 <- f <- vector("numeric", k)

for (i in 1:k) {
    s <- sqrt((p^2 * q^2 - 4)/(p^2 + q^2 - 5))
    si <- 1/s
    d1[i] <- p * q
    d2[i] <- m * s - p * q/2 + 1
    r <- (1 - w[i]^si)/w[i]^si
    f[i] <- r * d2[i]/d1[i]
    p <- p - 1
    q <- q - 1
}

pv <- pf(f, d1, d2, lower.tail = FALSE)

dmat <- cbind(WilksL = w, F = f, df1 = d1, df2 = d2, p = pv) %>%
  kable("html") %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped", full_width = F)

Wilks lambda pour la premi√®re composante canonique :

  • Œõ = 0.00215

  • F = 87.39

  • d.f. = 12, 114

  • p < 0.0001.

Wilks lambda is a ratio of two variance-covariance matrices (raised to a certain power). If the values of these statistics are large (small p-value), then we reject the null hypothesis. In our example, we reject the null hypothesis that there is no relationship between the two sets of variables and conclude that the two sets of variables are dependent. Note also that the above null hypothesis is equivalent to testing the null hypothesis that all p canonical variate pairs are uncorrelated, or

\(H_0: \rho^*_1 = \rho^*_2 = \dots = \rho^*_p = 0 \)

Because Wilks lambda is significant and the canonical correlations are ordered from largest to smallest, we can conclude that at least \(\rho^*_1 \ne 0\).

We may also wish to test the hypothesis that the second or the third canonical variate pairs are correlated. We can do this in successive tests. Next, test whether the second and third canonical variate pairs are correlated‚Ä¶

\(H_0: \rho^*_2 = \rho^*_3 = 0\)

We can look again at the SAS output above. In the second row for the likelihood ratio test statistic we find L‚Äô = 0.19524; F = 18.53; d.f. = 6, 88; p < 0.0001. From this test we can conclude that the second canonical variate pair is correlated, \(\rho^*_2 \ne 0\).

Finally, we can test the significance of the third canonical variate pair.

\(H_0: \rho^*_3 = 0\)

The third row of the SAS output contains the likelihood ratio test statistic L‚Äô = 0.8528; F = 3.88; d.f. = 2, 45; p = 0.0278. This is also significant and so we conclude that the third canonical variate pair is correlated.

All three canonical variate pairs are significantly correlated and dependent on one another. This suggests that we may summarize all three pairs. In practice, these tests are carried out successively until you find a non-significant result. Once a non-significant result is found, you stop. If this happens with the first canonical variate pair, then there is not sufficient evidence of any relationship between the two sets of variables and the analysis may stop.

If the first pair shows significance, then you move on to the second canonical variate pair. If this second pair is not significantly correlated then stop. If it was significant you would continue to the third pair, proceeding in this iterative manner through the pairs of canonical variates testing until you find non-significant results.
